 1920}}, "type": "video", "url": "https://t.co/ovNEa7td54", "video_info": {"aspect_ratio": [16, 9], "duration_millis": 45966, "variants": [{"content_type": "application/x-mpegURL", "url": "https://video.twimg.com/amplify_video/2052025924011573250/pl/kyO7XiHN18djjUfJ.m3u8?tag=27"}, {"bitrate": 256000, "content_type": "video/mp4", "url": "https://video.twimg.com/amplify_video/2052025924011573250/vid/avc1/480x270/X7v4AbAQnPDLWYsD.mp4?tag=27"}, {"bitrate": 832000, "content_type": "video/mp4", "url": "https://video.twimg.com/amplify_video/2052025924011573250/vid/avc1/640x360/VNQn2aIussW4xQtV.mp4?tag=27"}, {"bitrate": 2176000, "content_type": "video/mp4", "url": "https://video.twimg.com/amplify_video/2052025924011573250/vid/avc1/1280x720/5UhAa8omAG7WsE7i.mp4?tag=27"}, {"bitrate": 10368000, "content_type": "video/mp4", "url": "https://video.twimg.com/amplify_video/2052025924011573250/vid/avc1/1920x1080/flvwPh5xr-NJY9aP.mp4?tag=27"}]}}]}, "card": null, "place": {}, "entities": {"hashtags": [], "symbols": [], "timestamps": [], "urls": [], "user_mentions": []}, "quoted_tweet": null, "retweeted_tweet": null, "isLimitedReply": false, "communityInfo": null, "article": null}, {"type": "tweet", "id": "2052003033933042152", "url": "https://x.com/HighSignal_AI/status/2052003033933042152", "twitterUrl": "https://twitter.com/HighSignal_AI/status/2052003033933042152", "text": "Alexandr Wang on Why He's Waiting to Have Kids Until Brain-Computer Interfaces Work\n\nScale AI founder @alexandr_wang has an unusual reason for delaying fatherhood: he's waiting for Neuralink.\n\nWang explains that he wants to hold off on having kids until brain-computer interfaces actually start working . His reasoning comes down to neuroplasticity and the widening gap between AI and human intelligence.\n\n\"I want to wait to have kids until we figure out how Neurolink or other it's called brain computer interfaces. So other ways for brains to interlink with the computer um until they start working.\"\n\nHis first reason is biological:\n\n\"In your first like 7 years of life your brain is more neuroplastic than at any other point in your life like by by an order of magnitude. I think when we get neural link and we get these other technologies. Kids who are born with them are going to learn how to use them in like crazy crazy ways. Like it'll be a actually like a part of their brain in a way that it'll never be true for an adult who gets like a neural link or whatever hooked into their hooked into their brain.\"\n\nIn other words, a child raised with a brain-computer interface from infancy would integrate it natively in a way no retrofitted adult ever could.\n\nHis second reason is the mismatch in rates of improvement between AI and biology:\n\n\"Humans were only evolving at a certain rate. Humans will get smarter over time. It's just on the time scale of like millions of years because natural selection and evolution is really slow. So if you play this forward, right, like you're going to have AI that are going to continue getting smarter, continue improving, like they're going to keep improving really quickly. And you know, biology is going to improve only so fast.\"\n\nEvolution moves over millions of years. AI improves over months. That gap, in his view, is only going to grow.\n\nWhich leads to his conclusion:\n\n\"What we need at some point is the ability to tap into AI ourselves. Eventually, I think we're going to need some interlink or hookup between our brains directly to AI and the internet and all these things.\"\n\nHe doesn't dismiss the concerns. He acknowledges it's \"potentially dangerous\" and \"potentially terrifying and scary\" but argues it's not really optional:\n\n\"We just are going to have to do it. Like AI is going to go like this. Humans are going to improve at a much slower rate, and we're going to need to hook into that capability.\"", "source": "Twitter for iPhone", "retweetCount": 10, "replyCount": 0, "likeCount": 11, "quoteCount": 0, "viewCount"